AUT}} [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]]<br> {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Minas T\u00eanis Clube (men's volleyball)|Minas T\u00eanis Clube]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[\u0130stanbul B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi (volleyball team)|\u0130stanbul BBSK]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Paris Volley]]\n| nationalyears        = 2009\u20132015\n| nationalteam         = {{vb|USA}}\n| medaltemplates-title = Medal record\n| medaltemplates       =\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[volleyball]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|World Cup]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 Japan]] | }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FIVB World League|World League]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 Florence]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2012 FIVB Volleyball World League|2012 Sofia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Russell Kenneth Holmes''' (born 1 July 1982) is a former [[United States|American]] [[volleyball player]], a member of the [[United States men's national volleyball team]], a participant of the [[Olympic Games]] [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], gold medalist of the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|2014 World League]] and [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|2015 World Cup]], silver medalist of the [[2012 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League 2012]], two\u2013time Austrian Champion (2009, 2010), [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]).\n\n==Personal life==\nHolmes was born in [[Anaheim, California]], [[United States]]. His parents are Mark and Tamara Holmes. He has an older sister Leah and a younger brother Dane. After graduating from Fountain Valley High School in 2001, he served a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|mission]] for [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] from 2001\u20132003 in [[London]], [[England]]. He graduated from [[Brigham Young University]] in 2008 with a degree in [[sociology]]. He is married to Krystal. He has two daughters and son \u2013 Sadie Rae (born in June 2007 - from his first marriage), Shea Golden (born on April 27, 2015) and Liam Russell (born on August 10, 2017)\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn 2008\u20132010, he played overseas for Austria's [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]] in the Middle European Volleyball Zone Association (MEVZA), winning the MEVZA Cup in 2009 and the Austrian Cup in 2009 and 2010.\n\nDuring the winter of 2010\u20132011, Russell played for [[Minas T\u00eanis Clube (men's volleyball)|Minas T\u00eanis Clube]] in [[Brazilian Men's Volleyball Superliga|Brazilian Volleyball League]]. During 2011\u201313, he played for Poland\u2019s [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]] in the [[PlusLiga]] and then for Turkey's [[\u0130stanbul B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi (volleyball team)|\u0130stanbul BBSK]] during the 2013\u20132014 season in the [[Turkish Men's Volleyball League]]. While playing in Istanbul, BBSK reached the Final Four of the CEV Challenge Cup.\n\nIn 2014 he returned to [[PlusLiga]], this time playing for [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.plusliga.pl/news/id/9620 ''Russell Holmes w Asseco Resovii''] \u2013 plusliga.pl \u2013 05-08-2014</ref> In April 2015 he achieved title of Polish Champion with club from [[Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.worldofvolley.com/News/Latest_news/Poland/51403/pol-m-madhouse-in-rzeszw--resovia-is-new-polish-champion.html ''POL M: Madhouse in Rzesz\u00f3w \u2013 Resovia is new Polish champion!''] \u2013 worldofvolley.com \u2013 28-04-2015</ref>\n\n===National team===\nHolmes made his [[Olympic games|Olympic]] debut with the [[United States men's national volleyball team|U.S. national team]] at [[2012 Olympics|Olympic Games 2012]] in [[London]], [[Great Britain]].\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''[[CEV Champions League]]'''\n** [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|2014/2015]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n\n* '''[[FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|FIVB Club World Championship]]'''\n** [[File:Silver medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2011 FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|Qatar 2011]] \u2013 with [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2008/2009''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Austrian Cup, with [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]]\n** '''2008/2009''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Austrian Championship, with [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]]\n** '''2009/2010''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Austrian Cup, with [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]]\n** '''2009/2010''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Austrian Championship, with [[Hypo Tirol Innsbruck]]\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012\u201313 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Turkish Men's Volleyball League|Turkish Championship]], with [[\u0130stanbul B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi (volleyball team)|\u0130stanbul BBSK]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n** '''2015/2016''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015\u201316 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2012''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2012 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup|FIVB World Cup]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2011:''' [[2011 FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|FIVB Club World Championship]] \u2013 Best Middle Blocker\n* '''2016:''' [[2015\u201316 CEV Champions League|CEV Champions League]] \u2013 Best Middle Blocker\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.teamusa.org/usa-volleyball/athletes/Russell-Holmes Team USA profile]\n* [http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/427 PlusLiga Player profile]\n\n{{United States men's volleyball squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Volleyball 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{United States men volleyball team 2015 FIVB World Cup}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box |\n  | before = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Piotr Nowakowski]]<br>{{flagicon|NED}} [[Rob Bontje]]\n  | after = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Marko Podrascanin]]<br>{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Artem Volvich]]\n  | title = Best Middle Blocker of <br>[[CEV Champions League]]\n  | years = [[2015\u201316 CEV Champions League|2015/2016]]<br /> <small>ex aequo {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Sebasti\u00e1n Sol\u00e9]]</small>\n|}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holmes, Russell}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Anaheim, California]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in England]]\n[[Category:American men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Olympic volleyball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Austrian Champions of men's volleyball]]\n[[Category:BYU Cougars men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel players]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from California]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Holmes_(volleyball)"}
{"title_page": "Martin Solveig discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = [[Martin Solveig]]\n| Logo         =\n| Image        = Martin_Solveig_Pukkelpop_2009.jpg\n| Caption      = Solveig at [[Pukkelpop]] music festival\n| Studio       = 5\n| Compilation  = 1\n| Live         =\n| Video        =\n| Music videos =\n| Singles      = 26\n}}\n\nThe discography of [[Martin Solveig]], a French DJ and record producer, consists of four [[studio album]]s, one [[compilation album]] and twenty-six [[Single (music)|singles]] (including one as a featured artist).\n\nHis debut studio album, ''Sur la terre'', was released in June 2002. The album includes the singles \"[[Madan (song)|Madan]]\", \"[[Rocking Music]]\" and \"[[I'm a Good Man]]\".\n\nHis second studio album, ''Hedonist'', was released in September 2005, the album peaked at number 43 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]. The album includes the singles \"[[Everybody (Martin Solveig song)|Everybody]]\", \"[[Jealousy (Martin Solveig song)|Jealousy]]\", \"Something Better\" and \"[[Rejection (song)|Rejection]]\".\n\nHis third studio album, ''[[C'est la Vie (Martin Solveig album)|C'est la Vie]]'', was released in October 2008, the album peaked at number 16 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]].  \"[[C'est la Vie (Martin Solveig song)|C'est la Vie]]\" was released as the lead single from the album on 21 January 2008. \"[[I Want You (Martin Solveig song)|I Want You]]\" was released as the second single from the album on 15 September 2008. \"[[One 2.3 Four]]\" was released as the third single from the album on 22 December 2008. \"[[Boys & Girls (Martin Solveig song)|Boys & Girls]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album on 28 September 2009.\n\nHis fourth studio album, ''[[Smash (Martin Solveig album)|Smash]]'', was released in June 2011, peaking at number 18 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]. On 6 September 2010 he released the single \"[[Hello (Martin Solveig song)|Hello]]\" with [[Dragonette]] as the lead single from the album. It is Solveig's most successful single to date, peaking at number one in [[Austria]], [[Belgium]] ([[Flanders]]), [[Czech Republic]] and the [[Netherlands]], while charting within the top 10 in ten other countries. The song also peaked at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. \"[[Ready 2 Go]]\" was released as the second single from the album on 28 March 2011. On 24 October 2011 \"[[Big in Japan (Martin Solveig song)|Big in Japan]]\" was released as the third single from the album. On 2 April 2012 \"[[The Night Out]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album.\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11.5em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18.5em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br/><ref name=\"FRA\">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Martin+Solveig|title=Discographie Martin Solveig|publisher=French Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL (Fl)]]<br/><ref name=\"FL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Martin+Solveig|title=Discografie Martin Solveig|publisher=Belgium (Flanders) Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL (Wa)]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br/><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/|title=Discographie Martin Solveig|format=enter \"Martin Solveig\" into the \"Suchen\" box|publisher=German Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</