| top score1 = 106\n| deliveries1 = 6,215\n| wickets1 = 84\n| bowl avg1 = 35.79\n| fivefor1 = 4\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 7/66\n| catches/stumpings1 = 65/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 126\n| runs2 = 1,871\n| bat avg2 = 24.94\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/9\n| top score2 = 89\n| deliveries2 = 4,956\n| wickets2 = 81\n| bowl avg2 = 47.54\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 4/26\n| catches/stumpings2 = 67/\u2013\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 96\n| runs3 = 3,549\n| bat avg3 = 23.81\n| 100s/50s3 = 2/21\n| top score3 = 121\n| deliveries3 = 13,744\n| wickets3 = 217\n| bowl avg3 = 28.81\n| fivefor3 = 10\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 7/66\n| catches/stumpings3 = 137/\u2013\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 191\n| runs4 = 3,092\n| bat avg4 = 24.93\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/14\n| top score4 = 89\n| deliveries4 = 7,654\n| wickets4 = 154\n| bowl avg4 = 37.98\n| fivefor4 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 5/16\n| catches/stumpings4 = 104/\u2013\n| date = 19 March\n| year = 2019\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/player/53115.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Darren Julius Garvey Sammy''' (born 20 December 1983) is a [[Saint Lucia]]n [[cricket]]er who played international cricket for the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]]. He is also an honorary Pakistani citizen. He is a two time [[ICC World Twenty20|T20 World Cup]] winning captain. On making his [[One-Day International]] (ODI) debut against Bangladesh in 2004, Sammy became the first person from the island of St Lucia to play international cricket. Three years later he made his Test debut against England, taking 7/66 which were the best bowling figures for a West Indian in his first Test since [[Alf Valentine]] in 1950. Sammy was appointed West Indies captain in October 2010. He scored his maiden Test century in May 2012 during a match against England.\n\nSammy is the only captain to have won World T20 twice. He captained West Indies to the [[2012 ICC World Twenty20]] victory against [[Sri Lanka]], West Indies' first major trophy for 8 years (having won the ICC Champions trophy against England in 2004).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/match-report/samuels-special-spur-epic-west-indies-win/29853 |title=Samuels special the spur for epic West Indies win |publisher=Wisden India |date=7 October 2012}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=January 2020}} Sammy again captained West Indies to victory in the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]] against England.<ref>[http://m.firstpost.com/sports/explained-why-did-captain-darren-sammy-lay-into-west-indies-board-soon-after-winning-icc-world-t20-title-2711172.html Why did Sammy lay into West Indies board soon after winning ICC World T20 title: All you need to know] Firstpost</ref> Sammy captained [[Peshawar Zalmi]] in the [[Pakistan Super League]] from 2017 until 2020, when he stepped down due to fitness.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peshawar Zalmi win Pakistan Super League 2017 |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1318595 |website=Dawn}}</ref> He then agreed to a two-year head coaching contract for [[Peshawar Zalmi]], a position he currently holds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Darren Sammy appointed head coach, Wahab Riaz new captain of Peshawar Zalmi|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1538652/darren-sammy-appointed-head-coach-wahab-riaz-new-captain-of-peshawar-zalmi|website=Dawn}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2016, Sammy was informed he was being dropped as Test captain of [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/81871/wont-be-west-indies-t20i-captain-anymore-darren-sammy |title=Won't be West Indies' T20I captain anymore: Darren Sammy |publisher=Cricbuzz |date=5 August 2016 |accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor his part in bringing back international cricket to Pakistan, Sammy will receive the highest civilian medal of Pakistan, [[Nishan-e-Pakistan]] on 23 March,2020. He will also be awarded with honorary Pakistani citizenship by the [[President of Pakistan]] [[Arif Alvi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28755939/darren-sammy-become-honorary-citizen-pakistan-march-23 |title=Darren Sammy to become honorary citizen of Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/darren-sammy-pakistan-honorary-citizenship-march-23-pakistan-super-league-2020-1649016-2020-02-22 |title=Darren Sammy given honorary citizenship of Pakistan on March 23 |work=India Today |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Debut==\nOn 2 October 2001 Daren Sammy made his [[List A cricket|List&nbsp;A]] debut at the age of 17. Playing in the [[Red Stripe Bowl]] for the Northern Windward Islands against [[Jamaica national cricket team|Jamaica]] he bowled nine overs without taking a wicket and scored 25&nbsp;runs before he was [[run out]] as his team slid to defeat.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/73/73125.html |title=a13729 Jamaica v Northern Windward Islands: Red Stripe Bowl 2001/02 (Zone A) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> Playing three matches Sammy was his team's second-highest run-scorer with 90&nbsp;runs,<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/WI/Red_Stripe_Bowl_2001-02/Batting_by_Runs.html |title=Batting and Fielding in Red Stripe Bowl 2001/02 (Ordered by Runs) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> and took one wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/WI/Red_Stripe_Bowl_2001-02/Bowling_by_Wickets.html |title=Bowling in Red Stripe Bowl 2001/02 (ordered by wickets) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> Sammy was a member of the West Indies team to the 2002 Under-19 World Cup, which was held that year in New Zealand; he made 22 runs and took three wickets. Other members of that team, which lost to Australia in the  semi-final, included [[Dwayne Bravo]], [[Narsingh Deonarine]], [[Ravi Rampaul]], [[Shane Shillingford]], [[Lendl Simmons]], and [[Gavin Tonge]] all of whom went on to play for the West Indies senior team.\n\nUpon his return from New Zealand, Sammy was picked to attend the Shell Cricket Academy at [[St. George's University]] in [[Grenada]] in 2002. The scheme aimed to help what were considered the Caribbean's \"brightest cricketing prospects\" develop skills to help them professionally, including areas such as money management to complement their cricketing ability. Other notable players in that class{{spaced ndash}}just a handful would go on to play senior cricket for West Indies{{spaced ndash}}included [[Dwayne Smith]], [[Narsingh Deonarine]], [[Carlton Baugh]], [[Daren Powell]], and [[Omari Banks]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/118814.html |title=Shell Academy Set To Welcome New Entrants |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 March 2002 |last=Nicholas |first=Derrick |accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2003, Sammy made his first-class debut for the [[Windward Islands cricket team|Windward Islands]] against [[Barbados national cricket team|Barbados]] in the 2002/03 [[Carib Beer Cup]]. Batting at [[batting order (cricket)|number seven]], he scored no runs before being dismissed by spin bowler [[Sulieman Benn]] in the first innings, but fared better in the second, scoring 25 and falling to Benn again. Sammy bowled six overs in the match without taking a wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/76/76449.html |title=f47110 Windward Islands v Barbados: Carib Beer Cup 2002/03 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> He played one further match in that season's cup,<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44210/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-class matches played by Darren Sammy |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> again succumbing for a [[duck (cricket)|duck]] in the first innings and failing to take a wicket. In the second innings he recorded his maiden first-class half-century, scoring 53&nbsp;runs from 70&nbsp;balls before he was dismissed by spin bowler [[Mahendra Nagamootoo]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/76/76756.html |title=f47200 Guyana v Windward Islands: Carib Beer Cup 2002/03 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription|accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> At the start of the 2003 season in England, Sammy joined the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Young Cricketers. Whilst still a member of the Young Cricketers, Sammy was called to the West Indies to join the [[University of the West Indies]] Vice Chancellor's XI against England in a warm-up match.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.lords.org/latest-news/news-archive/mcc-young-cricketer-selected-by-west-indies,357,NS.html |title=MCC Young Cricketer selected by West Indies |date=22 May 2004 |publisher=Lords.org |accessdate=18 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613051424/http://lords.org/latest-news/news-archive/mcc-young-cricketer-selected-by-west-indies%2C357%2CNS.html |archivedate=13 June 2010  }}</ref>\n\n==International cricket career==\n\n===First international experience===\nFollowing a successful domestic season in which Sammy finished as the Windward Islands' second highest wicket-taker in the [[Regional Four Day Competition]] with 22&nbsp;scalps and 261&nbsp;runs, he was the only uncapped player selected in the 15-man West Indies squad for the NatWest Triangular One Day International Series with England and New Zealand in June 2004. Counting in favour of his selection was Sammy's experience of English conditions: in 2003 he played for Barnes Cricket Club in the [[Middlesex County Cricket League|Middlesex Premier Cricket League]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/139368.html |title=Daren Sammy named in Windies ODI squad |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 May 2004 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref> He subsequently earned his first West Indies cap in odd circumstances. Due to heavy rain the West Indies' match against New Zealand at the [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]] was abandoned without a ball being bowled. But the captains had already completed the toss, and the fixture counts in ICC records as Sammy's first match.<ref name=Lawson>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/135453.html |title=Sammy replaces Lawson for Champions Trophy |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 August 2004 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September, Sammy was recalled to the senior team in place of 22-year-old Jamaican fast bowler [[Jermaine Lawson]] who withdrew from the [[2004 ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy]] squad with a stress fracture of the lower back.<ref name=Lawson /> Sammy, at the age of 20, became the first international cricketer to emerge from St Lucia. For his actual playing debut, back at the Rose Bowl, Sammy took 1&nbsp;wicket for 19&nbsp;runs (1/19) off six overs and held on to three catches as West Indies beat Bangladesh by 138&nbsp;runs. It was the only match Sammy played in the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/143312.html |title=Gayle and Dillon outclass Bangladesh |first=Jenny |last=Thompson |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 September 2004 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44210/One-Day_International_Matches.html |title=One-Day International matches played by Darren Sammy |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=12 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421080722/http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44210/One-Day_International_Matches.html |archivedate=21 April 2009  }}</ref> The West Indies went on to win the trophy, beating England in the final.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/428237.html |title=West Indies win the Champions Trophy |first=Vaneisa |last=Baksh |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=4 October 2009 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Early international career===\nWhen the West Indies toured India in January 2007 Sammy was included in the squad, with a chance to make his Test debut. However, shortly before the team departed, he suffered an injury that ruled him out of the tour. After that set-back, Sammy travelled to England in April and May where he played in the [[Central Lancashire Cricket League|Central Lancashire League]] ahead of the West Indies' [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2007|tour of the country in May]]. He was selected in the touring squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvwi/content/story/293678.html |title=Sammy keen for Test debut |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 May 2007 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2313178/West-Indies-bowlers-rue-washout.html |title=West Indies bowlers rue washout |first=Paul |last=Bolton |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> This time, the team won the NatWest limited overs series. And the 23-year-old St Lucian won his first Test cap in the third Test match at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] on 7 June. He claimed his first Test wicket when he dismissed [[Alastair Cook]] caught by Dwayne Bravo, but his first innings was unremarkable save for his economy, giving up just 1.88 runs per over off 17 completed overs. In the second innings, though, Sammy caught England captain [[Michael Vaughan]] off his own bowling, with the England score 99/2. In his 17th over, he had [[Ian Bell]] caught behind by Ramdin. Next ball he had [[Matt Prior]] by the same route. A couple of balls later, on the same score he dismissed [[Liam Plunkett]], caught by Bravo. Five wickets gone, four to Sammy, three in five balls. He continued his excellent debut, capturing the wickets of [[Steve Harmison]] and [[Monty Panesar]], before snagging [[Paul Collingwood]] to end with seven wickets for 66 runs.<ref name=\"espncricinfo\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/258461.html |title=3rd Test: England v West Indies at Manchester, Jun 7\u201311, 2007 |accessdate=13 December 2011 |work=espncricinfo}}</ref> His bowling figures were the best at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] since [[Malcolm Marshall]]'s 7/22 in 1988, and the best by any West Indian on debut since [[Alf Valentine]] took 8/102 in 1950.\n\nAs an all-rounder Sammy did not cover himself in glory on that tour, averaging just 14.20 runs from 10 innings, twice unbeaten. He had just the tenth highest aggregate on a tour that included matches against Scotland and the Netherlands. As a bowler, he excelled with a team-best average of 17.72, 18&nbsp;wickets (third on the team) from 93.5 overs (five other players bowled more overs than Sammy).\n\nSammy was called up to the [[Stanford Superstars]], a team compiled by American billionaire [[Allen Stanford]], when Dwayne Bravo pulled out with an injury. He was not slated to play the first game, but Shivnarine Chanderpaul had a neck strain that precluded his participation. So all Sammy did was to provide electric fielding and consistent bowling to force his way into the side. As expected, the Superstars made it to the series finale to face England. The prize money at stake was US$20 million, $1 million each to the players on the winning team. Bowling first, the Superstars dismissed England for 99&nbsp;runs. Sammy took 2/13 and made one catch. He did not bat in the series.\n\nDuring the 2008/09 Regional Four Day Competition, Sammy played seven matches for the Windward Islands, scoring 476 runs at an average of 43.27 (the second highest for the club that season)<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/WI/Regional_Four_Day_Competition_2008-09/Batting_by_Average.html |title=Batting and Fielding in Regional Four Day Competition 2008/09 (Ordered by Average) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref> and recording his maiden first-class century. His innings of 121 came from 140&nbsp;balls and was scored against [[Barbados national cricket team|Barbados]] who were fielding a bowling line up including [[Tino Best]], Kemar Roach, and [[Corey Collymore]] who all had international experience. During the innings he also passed 2,000&nbsp;runs in first-class cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/205/205199.html |title=f51497 Barbados v Windward Islands: Regional Four Day Competition 2008/09 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref> Sammy took 23&nbsp;wickets in the competition at an average of 21.65.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/WI/Regional_Four_Day_Competition_2008-09/Bowling_by_Average.html |title=Bowling in Regional Four Day Competition 2008/09 (Ordered by Average) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, there was a pay dispute between the [[West Indies Players Association|West Indies players]] and the [[West Indies Cricket Board]] (WICB). An understrength squad was picked for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|series against Bangladesh]]. Of the 15&nbsp;players named, nine were uncapped; Sammy was appointed vice-captain and in the Test seven West Indies players made their debut.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/413237.html |title=West Indies name replacement squad |work=ESPNcricinfo |author=Cricinfo staff |date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=10 July 2009}}</ref> The West Indies lost the series 2\u20130 as Bangladesh secured their first overseas series win.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415358.html |title=Raqibul and Shakib inspire first overseas series win |last=Veera |first=Sriram |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> Sammy was the West Indies second-highest wicket-taker in the series with 12&nbsp;wickets at an average of 17.33.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref> he also scored 90&nbsp;runs at an average of 22.50.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Darren Sammy, 2010.jpg|thumb|Sammy training in February 2010 during the West Indies' [[West Indian cricket team in Australia in 2009\u201310|tour of Australia]]]]\nThe WICB announced its central contracts in November 2009, and Sammy was included in the 33-man list. He was given a Grade&nbsp;B contract (the second-highest level) worth $80,000.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/434197.html |title=Injured Fidel Edwards' contract withheld by WICB |first=Tony |last=Cozier |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/473499.html |title=Benn, Sammy in line for enhanced central contracts |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 August 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> His career-best Man of the Match figures of 4\u201326 in the third ODI in Saint Vincent & the Grenadines would have been more flattering still had captain Chris Gayle been able to hold on to a catch that would have given the tall Saint Lucian the distinction of becoming the first West Indian to take a five-fer in every form of the game; he had 5\u201326 off the same opponents in a Twenty20 International earlier in the series. West Indies bowled Zimbabwe for 104, having made 245.\n\nIn the fourth ODI, Sammy took 1\u201324 as West Indies won by four wickets; in the final match, he had 3\u201333 as West Indies again won by four wickets. Sammy finished the series as West Indies' joint top wicket-taker, himself and Kemar Roach sharing 16 scalps equally.\n\nPlaying at home, the West Indies had high hopes for the 2010 version of the Twenty20 competition.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/content/story/459364.html |title=West Indies crash out to ruthless Australia |last=English |first=Peter |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref> The tournament did not start off too badly, Sammy scoring 30 as the West Indies made 138\u20139 against Ireland, then capturing 3\u20138 and holding on to a record four catches as Ireland were routed for just 68, the second-lowest total in Twenty20s, and losing by 70 runs. But eventually West Indies were knocked out of contention when they were drubbed by Australia at [[Darren Sammy National Cricket Stadium|Beausejour Cricket Ground]] in Saint Lucia. He had a forgettable match in front of his home crowd, but overall, Sammy had had a good series. He ended with 51 runs in four innings, the fourth highest aggregate for West Indies, and his 12.75 was the seventh best average. But as a bowler, his six wickets and average of 12.0 topped the West Indies, and his economy rate of 5.26 runs per over was second.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5195;type=tournament |title=ICC World Twenty20, 2010 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=12 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316233155/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5195%3Btype%3Dtournament |archivedate=16 March 2014  }}</ref>\n\nIn the second ODI against South Africa at the [[Sir Vivian Richards Stadium]] in Antigua-Barbuda, West Indies appeared well on their way to a second consecutive loss. 200\u20136 in the 41st over, well short of their winning target of 301, Sammy joined Dwayne Bravo at the crease. But six sixes and two fours later, it looked as though West Indies might just win. Sammy had amassed 58 runs, the fifty coming up off just twenty deliveries. It was the fastest fifty ever by a West Indies player, and more importantly, it had brought West Indies within reach of victory.\nBut successive run-outs&nbsp;\u2013 [[Denesh Ramdin]], [[Ravi Rampaul]] and [[Nikita Miller]] all went by that route&nbsp;\u2013 left Sammy stranded and the West Indies 17 runs shy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/west-indies-v-south-africa-2010/engine/match/439148.html?innings=2;page=1;view=commentary |title=2nd ODI: West Indies v South Africa at North Sound, May 24, 2010 \u2013 Cricket Commentary |work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===West Indies captain===\nOn 17 October 2010 Sammy was named captain of the West Indies Test team for its tour to Sri Lanka and until the end of the 2011 season, replacing [[Chris Gayle]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/sri-lanka-v-west-indies-2010/content/story/482267.html |title=Darren Sammy named West Indies captain |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 October 2010 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> At the time Sammy had played 8&nbsp;Tests and 41&nbsp;ODIs.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44210/Test_Matches.html |title=Test matches played by Daren Sammy |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44210/ODI_Matches.html |title=ODI matches played by Daren Sammy |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> The previous captain and vice, Chris Gayle and [[Dwayne Bravo]] respectively, had chosen not to sign central contracts with the West Indies Cricket Board and were replaced.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/sri-lanka-v-west-indies-2010/content/current/story/482267.html |title=Daren Sammy named West Indies captain |date=17 October 2010 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> Between January 2004 and the start of the [[West Indian cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2010\u201311|tour to Sri Lanka]] in November, the West Indies had won just five of their previous 62&nbsp;Tests and were expected to lose the three match series against a team with a good home record.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/484012.html |title=Bowling West Indies' biggest worry |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=S |last=Rajesh |date=29 October 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In a series shortened by poor weather Sammy scored 10 runs and took two wickets at an average of 75.50,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5948;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Sri Lanka Test Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129183525/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5948%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=29 November 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5948;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Sri Lanka Test Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208061920/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5948%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=8 December 2010  }}</ref> and while he said he wanted to improve his own performance Sammy stated that he was pleased with the 0\u20130 result of the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/sri-lanka-v-west-indies-2010/content/story/490554.html |title=Happy with drawn result&nbsp;\u2013 Sammy |first=Sa'adi |last=Thawfeeq |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 December 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In the 2\u20130 defeat to Sri Lanka in the subsequent ODI series,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/sri-lanka-v-west-indies-2010/content/story/499696.html |title=Sri Lanka take series with 26-run win |first=Sa'adi |last=Thawfeeq |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 February 2011 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> Sammy scored 28&nbsp;runs and sent down 19&nbsp;wicketless overs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5949;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Sri Lanka ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5949;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Sri Lanka ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: left; margin-left: 1em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | '''Sammy's record as captain as of 30 April 2013'''\n|-\n| &nbsp; || Matches || Won || Lost || Drawn || Tied || No result\n|-\n| Test<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/WestIndies/Test/Miscellaneous/Captains/Playing_Record_Captain_Overall.html |title=West Indies captains' playing record in Test matches |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> || 25 || 8 || 8 || 9 || 0 || \u2013\n|-\n| ODI<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/WestIndies/ODI/Miscellaneous/Captains/Playing_Record_Captain_Overall.html |title=West Indies captains' playing record in ODI matches |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> || 51 || 19 || 30 || \u2013 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| T20I<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/WestIndies/International_Twenty20/Miscellaneous/Captains/Playing_Record_Captain_Overall.html |title=West Indies captains' playing record in International Twenty20 matches |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> || 21 || 12 || 7 || \u2013 || 1 || 1\n|}\nPakistan [[Pakistani cricket team in the West Indies in 2011|toured the West Indies]] in April and May 2011 for a T20I, five ODIs, and two Tests. In the first match of the Test series West Indies secured their first victory since 2009, ending a 17-match run without a win. Sammy took seven wickets in the match, including five in Pakistan's second innings, and was named Man of the Match for his performance.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-pakistan-2011/content/story/515603.html |title=Gibson hails West Indies spirit |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 May 2011 |accessdate=20 May 2011}}</ref> West Indies lost the second match, drawing the series 1\u20131; Sammy was his team's second-highest wicket-taker, claiming ten at an average of 17.90.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6343;type=series |title=Records / Pakistan in West Indies Test Series, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> The following month Sammy was named T20I player of the year at the [[West Indies Players Association]] awards.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/518208.html |title=Chris Gayle wins big at WIPA awards |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 June 2011 |accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref> When India [[Indian cricket team in the West Indies in 2011|toured in June and July]] the West Indies lost the Test series 1\u20130. [[Cricinfo]] recorded that Sammy led with passion and \"bowled his heart out\";<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-india-2011/content/current/story/522704.html |title=Opportunity lost for India in hard-fought series win |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sriram |last=Veera |date=11 July 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> he finished with seven wickets from three matches at an average of 38.28.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6340;type=series |title=Records / India in West Indies Test Series, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914235500/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6340%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=14 September 2011  }}</ref> While playing, Sammy had to deal with distractions from hostile crowds and pundits who criticised his appointment as captain as some believed he could not hold down a place as a player alone.<ref name=criticism>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-india-2011/content/story/520460.html |title=Sammy not deterred by criticism |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sriram |last=Veera |date=22 June 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nInitially named as captain until the end of the 2011 season, Sammy was retained as captain across all formats for the tours of Bangladesh and India.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/529294.html |title=West Indies name young squad for England T20s |date=23 August 2011 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In October Sammy's Grade&nbsp;B central contract was renewed; he was one of four players with a Grade&nbsp;B contract, the second highest category (Shivnarine Chanderpaul was the only player with a Grade&nbsp;A).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/535292.html |title=Samuels, Fidel Edwards given WICB contracts |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 October 2011 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> Later that month, the West Indies [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|toured Bangladesh]]. Sammy missed the first ODI through illness,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/536332.html |title=Simmons century sets up comfortable win |first=Siddarth |last=Ravindran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 October 2011 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> but returned to captain the side in the remaining two. West Indies won the series 2\u20131 and Sammy took two wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=25 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015050127/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=15 October 2011  }}</ref> The first Test was curtailed by rain and ended in a draw, and Sammy top-scored for his team. Having played 17&nbsp;Tests, the innings of 58&nbsp;runs from 43&nbsp;balls was Sammy's first half-century in the format.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/537832.html |title=Bangladesh enjoy better of rain-affected draw |first=Siddhartha |last=Talya |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 October 2011 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> West Indies won the second Test to take the series, and in the process Sammy dismissed Bangladesh all-rounder [[Shakib Al Hasan]] to claim his 50th&nbsp;Test wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/350/350362.html |title=f53463 t2012 Bangladesh v West Indies: West Indies in Bangladesh 2011/12 (2nd Test) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=7 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing on from the Bangladesh series, the West Indies moved on to India in November for [[West Indian cricket team in India in 2011\u201312|three Tests and five ODIs]]. West Indies lost the Test series 2\u20130 and Sammy finished as his team's highest wicket-taker with nine at an average of 34.77.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6930;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in India Test Series, 2011/12 /Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213212425/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6930%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=13 February 2012  }}</ref> In the ODI series, Sammy took a single wicket from 21.5&nbsp;overs as West Indies succumbed to a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6938;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in India ODI Series, 2011/12 /Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> The West Indies [[Australian cricket team in the West Indies in 2011\u201312|faced Australia]] in a five-match ODI series in March 2012. Sammy's team won the second match by five wickets, ending a series of 13 defeats against Australia that extended back to 2006.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-australia-2012/content/story/557782.html |title=West Indies end five-year drought |first=Daniel |last=Brettig |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 March 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref> The West Indies entered the final match with a 2\u20131 lead and a chance to register their first series win against Australia since 1995.  In the event Australia won by 30&nbsp;runs, but the margin of victory was smaller than it would have been had Sammy not scored 84&nbsp;runs from 50&nbsp;deliveries, his highest score in the format and an effort for which he was named Man of the Match.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-australia-2012/content/story/558695.html |title=Sammy heroics in vain as Australia draw series |first=Brydon |last=Coverdale |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 March 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref> In the Test series that followed, Sammy managed just five wickets from three matches at an average just above forty.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=7009;type=series |title=Records / The Frank Worrell Trophy, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=28 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501230428/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=7009%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=1 May 2012  }}</ref> As a batsman he was more successful, and was one of three West Indies batsmen to score more than 150&nbsp;runs in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=7009;type=series |title=Records / The Frank Worrell Trophy, 2011/12 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=28 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429051935/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=7009%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=29 April 2012  }}</ref> With the West Indies on 13/2 chasing 215 to win from 61&nbsp;overs on the final day of the second Test, Sammy promoted himself up the [[batting order (cricket)|batting order]] to number three to accelerate the scoring rate. He managed 30 [[not out]] from 26&nbsp;deliveries before rain intervened and the match ended in a draw.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-australia-2012/content/story/561838.html |title=Rain ends prospect of intriguing finish |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 April 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> West Indies lost the third Test by 75&nbsp;runs to lose the series 2\u20130, but during his team's chase of 370 to win on the final day Sammy scored his second Test half-century, 61 from 51&nbsp;deliveries, bettering his previous highest Test score of 58.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/419/419192.html |title=f54012 t2042 West Indies v Australia: Australia in West Indies 2011/12 (3rd Test) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Trent Bridge, 2012 England v West Indies Test.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Sammy and [[Marlon Samuels]] batting against England at [[Trent Bridge]] in May 2012. During the 204-run partnership Sammy scored his maiden Test century.]]\nThe 2011/12 season saw Sammy improve as a batsman: in the series against India and Australia Sammy scored over 100&nbsp;runs, which he had not done previously in a Test series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/53115.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting;view=series |title=Statistics / Statsguru / DJG Sammy / Test, matches / batting analysis / series averages |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> This trend continued when the West Indies toured England in May 2012. Sammy began the series with scores of 17 and 37 in the first Test at Lord's, during which he passed 3,000&nbsp;runs in first-class cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/353/353720.html |title=f54044 t2043 England v West Indies: West Indies in England 2012 (1st Test) |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> In the following Test, in his 26th Test, Sammy registered his maiden Test century. It was just the seventh time a number eight batsman had scored a century for the West Indies. Sammy partnered [[Marlon Samuels]] in a 204-run stand, the second-highest for the West Indies' seventh wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/566269.html |title=Strauss hundred leads strong England reply |first=David |last=Hopps |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> The West Indies lost the Test and drew the next one to lose the series 2\u20130;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/568089.html |title=Damp Test ends with final-day washout |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 June 2012 |first=David |last=Hopps |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> Sammy finished with 201&nbsp;runs from five innings and was his team's third highest run-scorer in the series while his six wickets cost 48.50&nbsp;runs each.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6881;type=series |title=Records / The Wisden Trophy, 2012 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 June 2012}}<br />\u2022{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6881;type=series |title=Records / The Wisden Trophy, 2012 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> Commenting on Sammy's performance in the series, former West Indies captain [[Viv Richards]] said \"All of a sudden there was this new-found confidence. You need to have a leader who can come out to the middle and make some sort of contribution. He has done enough and should not feel he has one foot in and one foot out as far as the leadership in concerned. He has done his bit to provide a winning environment.\"<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/18407414 |title=Kevin Pietersen reminds me of Muhammad Ali&nbsp;\u2013 Sir Viv Richards |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealand [[New Zealand cricket team in the West Indies in 2012|toured the West Indies]] between June and August 2012. The fixtures included two Tests, five ODIs, and two T20Is, and the West Indies won every match apart from the third ODI.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-new-zealand-2012/content/series/560916.html?template=fixtures |title=New Zealand tour of United States of America and West Indies, 2012 / Fixtures |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref> Sammy guided the team to their first Test series victory since 2009 against a Test side other than minnows Bangladesh and Zimbabwe.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-new-zealand-2012/content/story/575727.html |title='This one's definitely for Jamaica' \u2013 Samuels |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 August 2012 |accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref> He carried on his good form with the bat, scoring a half-century in the first Test.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-new-zealand-2012/content/story/574452.html |title=New Zealand top order bridges gap |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 July 2012 |accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nSammy led the West Indies in the 2012 World Twenty20 hosted by Sri Lanka. For the first time in a long time, the West Indies were considered realistic contenders for the title, a measure of how the team has matured under the auspices of Sammy. However, it was as an individual player that he came under scrutiny in the tournament. In the journey from group stages to the final, Sammy contributed 27 runs with the bat from four visits to the crease and overall bowling figures of 2/125, and drew a lot of criticism as many people felt he was keeping better players out of the side. But in the final, when it mattered most, Sammy scored 26 not out from 15 balls and took two key wickets (almost matching his batting and bowling tally for the rest of the tournament) to help his team overcome a slow start and defeat Sri Lanka.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/content/story/583269.html |title=West Indies no-hopers no more |first=Siddarth |last=Ravindran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 September 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/content/story/585988.html |title=A triumph for Sammy |first=Jarrod |last=Kimber |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 October 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/content/current/story/585881.html |title=Samuels, Sammy give WI first world title since 1979 |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 October 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]] he along with [[Kemar Roach]] set the record for the highest 10th wicket partnership in [[ICC Champions Trophy]] history (51*)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?id=44;type=trophy|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} ICC Champions Trophy (ICC KnockOut) {{!}} Highest partnerships by wicket |work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2016, Beaus\u00e9jour Cricket Ground, a cricket ground located near Gros Islet, [[Saint Lucia|St Lucia]] having a [[seating capacity]] of 15,000 was renamed to the [[Darren Sammy National Cricket Stadium]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/995351.html |title=Saint Lucia renames stadium in honour of Daren Sammy |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref> This was done after Daren Sammy captained the [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] side in winning the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016 edition of ICC World Twenty20]] in India, their second [[ICC World T20|World T20]] title.\n\nIn August 2016 he was dropped as T20I captain and the chairman of selectors said he did not merit a place in the [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/westindies/content/story/1042939.html |title=I won't be T20 captain anymore \u2013 Sammy |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 August 2016 |accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> [[Carlos Brathwaite]] replaced him for the T20I leadership role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-india-2016/content/story/1044151.html |title=Carlos Brathwaite named West Indies T20 captain |date=9 August 2016 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, he was named in a [[World XI (cricket)|World XI]] side to play three Twenty20 International matches against Pakistan in the [[2017 Independence Cup (cricket)|2017 Independence Cup]] in [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"WXI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/1117616.html |title=Faf du Plessis named captain of World XI to travel to Pakistan |accessdate=24 August 2017 |work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic and T20 franchise career==\nAt the launch of the [[Caribbean Premier League]] Sammy was announced as a franchise player for the [[2013 Caribbean Premier League|2013 tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cplt20.com/news/caribbean-premier-league-announces-exciting-plans-tournament |title=Latest News \u2013 cplt20 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSammy played professionally in the [[Indian Premier League]] for [[Sunrisers Hyderabad|Hyderabad]], and he was made captain of that franchise in [[2014 Indian Premier League|2014]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/ipl-7-dhawan-named-skipper-of-sunrisers-sammy-vice-captain-1448317.html |title=IPL 7: Dhawan named skipper of Sunrisers, Sammy vice-captain \u2013 Firstpost |date=24 March 2014 |publisher=}}</ref> For the [[2015 Indian Premier League|2015 edition]], he was released by Hyderabad, and subsequently signed by [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricketcountry.com/news/darren-sammy-sold-for-rs-2-8-crore-to-royal-challengers-bangalore-rcb-251303|title=Daren Sammy sold for Rs. 2.8 crore to Royal Challengers Bangalore (RCB)|date=16 February 2015|work=Cricket Country|access-date=28 March 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> He was then picked up by [[Kings XI Punjab]] for the [[2017 Indian Premier League|2017 tournament]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/ipl-2017/ipl-2017-kings-xi-punjab-seek-redemption-after-forgettable-last-season/story-XZKlt0PsAsJAYecHzDTzQM.html|title=IPL\u20092017:\u2009Kings XI\u2009Punjab seek redemption after forgettable last season|date=28 March 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|access-date=28 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Chief Minister of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], [[Pervaiz Khattak]], offered the all-rounder honorary Pakistani citizenship in response to a special request by [[Peshawar Zalmi]] ownership, which Sammy accepted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arysports.tv/sammy-receives-honorary-pakistan-citizenship/ |title=Sammy receives honorary Pakistan citizenship |date=26 April 2016 |publisher=}}</ref> Sammy played for Peshawar Zalmi in the inaugural Pakistan Super League in 2016. In the 2016 PSL draft, he was retained by Peshawar Zalmi. During the draft, captain Shahid Afridi made the stunning announcement of naming Sammy the new captain of Peshawar Zalmi. With Sammy as its popular captain, the club won the [[Pakistan Super League 2017|second edition]] of the Pakistan Super League in 2017.\n\nIn May 2018, he was named as one of the ten marquee players for the [[2018 Global T20 Canada|first edition]] of the [[Global T20 Canada]] cricket tournament.<ref name=\"marquee1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1147584.html |title=Steven Smith named as marquee player for Canada T20 tournament |accessdate=24 May 2018 |work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref name=\"marquee2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/steve-smith-australia-cricket-global-t20-canada-ball-scuffing-scandal/1k2lxwrnwsazj1wj8ylmuejdbm |title=Steve Smith named as marquee player for Global T20 Canada |accessdate=24 May 2018 |work=Sporting News}}</ref> On 3 June 2018, he was selected to play for the Toronto Nationals in the players' draft for the inaugural edition of the tournament.<ref name=\"Squads1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/global-t20-canada-complete-squads |title=Global T20 Canada: Complete Squads |work=SportsKeeda |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Squads2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/global-t20-canada-league-full-squads-announced/ |title=Global T20 Canada League \u2013 Full Squads announced |work=CricTracker |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, he was selected to play for the Brampton Wolves franchise team in the [[2019 Global T20 Canada]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadacricket.com/?p=12755 |title=Global T20 draft streamed live |work=Canada Cricket Online |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing style==\n{{Quote box | quote=I have the term allrounder because I bowl, I bat and I field, but in reality I'm not really one thing or the other.|source=\u2014Daren Sammy, June 2007<ref name=workhorse>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/297959.html |title='I want to be the workhorse of the team' |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=Miller |date=14 June 2007 |accessdate=2011-07-12}}</ref>|align=right | width=33%}}\n\nSammy has a reputation for bowling long spells<ref name=workhorse /> and his medium-fast pace bowling is used to support strike bowlers. He has commented that \"We all have roles in the team and I've clearly understood what my role is in the team, which is to build pressure and be the workhorse of the team. I've accepted that and that's how I've played throughout my career.\"<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-pakistan-2011/content/story/515842.html |title=West Indies aim for rankings boost |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 May 2011 |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> He aims to do this by bowling dot balls to create pressure.<ref name=criticism /> Sammy feels that because he is a support bowler batsmen relax against him and are more prone to make mistakes.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/541920.html |title=Batsmen underestimate me&nbsp;\u2013 Sammy |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> A consistent bowler, though he does not move the ball much Sammy delivers the ball with an upright seam and uses the [[Crease (cricket)|crease]] to vary his angle of delivery.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-australia-2012/content/current/story/562364.html |title=An attack for England? |first=Daniel |last=Brettig |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref> As a batsman, his strike-rate in ODIs of 98.11 is the second highest amongst West Indian players who have faced at least 500&nbsp;deliveries (behind all-rounder [[Andre Russell]] on 119.34),<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/highest_career_strike_rate.html?class=2;id=4;type=team |title=Records / West Indies / One-Day Internationals / Highest strike rates |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> and in ODI innings of at least 25&nbsp;runs holds the second, third, and fourth highest strike rates of West Indian players.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/highest_strike_rate_innings.html?class=2;id=4;type=team |title=Records / West Indies / One-Day Internationals / Highest strike rates in an innings |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Cricket}}\n* [[List of West Indies cricketers who have taken five-wicket hauls on Test debut]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=53115}}\n* [http://www.royalchallengers.com/darren-sammy Darren Sammy Profile] from [[Royal Challengers Bangalore|RoyalChallengers]]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title= Captaincy\n| bg= #790D1A\n| fg= white\n| bordercolor=#F5BA0E\n| list1=\n{{West Indies Test Cricket Captains}}\n{{West Indies ODI Cricket Captains}}\n{{West Indies T20I Cricket Captains}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title= West Indies squads\n| bg= #790D1A\n| fg= white\n| bordercolor=#F5BA0E\n| list1=\n{{West Indies Squad 2004 ICC Champions Trophy}}\n{{West Indies Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{West Indies Squad 2012 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{West Indies Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{West Indies Squad 2016 ICC World Twenty20}}\n}}\n{{Peshawar Zalmi current squad}}\n{{Lucia Zouks Squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sammy, Darren}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Saint Lucian Christians]]\n[[Category:West Indies One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:West Indies Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:West Indies Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Windward Islands cricketers]]\n[[Category:Saint Lucian cricketers]]\n[[Category:St Lucia Zouks cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sunrisers Hyderabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Royal Challengers Bangalore cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who have taken five wickets on Test debut]]\n[[Category:West Indies Test cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Hobart Hurricanes cricketers]]\n[[Category:Hampshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Peshawar Zalmi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rangpur Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rajshahi Kings cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Micoud Quarter]]\n[[Category:World XI Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|West Indian cricketer}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Daren Sammy\n| image = DARREN SAMMY.jpg\n| caption = Sammy playing for the Invitational [[Prime Minister's XI]] in [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] in 2010\n| country = West Indies\n| fullname = Daren Sammy\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|12|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Micoud]], [[Saint Lucia]]\n| heightft = 6\n| heightinch = 4\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm medium-fast\n| role = [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowling]] [[all-rounder]]\n| international =